<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROSE COURT IS IN FULL BLOOM; 
</P>
<P>
CONTEST: THE QUEEN OF THE 102ND TOURNAMENT OF ROSES PARADE WILL BE SELECTED 
TUESDAY FROM AMONG THE SEVEN AMERICAN BEAUTIES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By VICKI TORRES, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PASADENA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
For 17-year-old Cara Payton Rullman, trying out for the Tournament of Roses 
Royal Court was just a lark, something that she and about 35 of her San Marino 
girlfriends decided to do this year. 
</P>
<P>
For 18-year-old Dawn Christine Gray of Pasadena, the competition represents a 
third, determined try for the coveted title of Rose Queen. The Rose Court is 
the closest Gray has come yet. 
</P>
<P>
"I think it's easier every year," she said of her previous attempts, "but 
everything that comes up now will be new." 
</P>
<P>
Despite different motives for entering the contest, both teen-agers ended up 
teary-eyed Monday after they were named to the seven-member court. More than 
700 young women competed this year at Tournament House in Pasadena in a 
three-week round of judging. The contest is open to residents of the Pasadena 
Community College District. 
</P>
<P>
The seven teen-agers compose an exotic-appearing court this year, reflecting 
the ethnic diversity of the San Gabriel Valley. Members include a young woman 
whose parents are from India, an African-American, a Japanese-American and a 
Chinese-American. 
</P>
<P>
Those named Monday were Tisha Mei-Lin Kong, 16, of San Marino, captain of the 
varsity tennis team at San Marino High School; Wendy Nicole Schnee, 17, of 
Pasadena, active on the student council at Westridge School; and Jessica Leigh 
Roegler, 17, of Altadena, principal violist in the John Muir High School 
Symphony. 
</P>
<P>
Also named were Harini Reddy, 17, of Arcadia, a Westridge student who takes 
Indian music classes; and Andrea Sae Uyeda, 16, of Pasadena, a Polytechnic 
School student and member of Zendeko Taiko, a Japanese drum group. 
</P>
<P>
Gray, a Pasadena City College student active in the National Assn. for the 
Advancement of Colored People, and Rullman, a San Marino High School varsity 
cheering squad member, complete the court. 
</P>
<P>
One of the seven will be named the Rose Queen on Tuesday. She presides over the 
102nd Tournament of Roses Parade, Jan. 1 in Pasadena. 
</P>
<P>
The parade, whose theme this year is "Fun 'n' Games," will be followed the same 
day by the 77th Rose Bowl game, featuring the Pacific 10 and Big Ten conference 
champions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
