<P>
Photo, BEST BET: "There are things we learn about growing up," Paul Linke said 
in a 1987 Times interview, "and there are some things that we never talk about. 
Death is one of them." Linke's unflinching monologue, "Time Flies When You're 
Alive," is about the death of his wife from cancer at the age of 37. It began 
at the Powerhouse and Tiffany theaters, in Santa Monica and West Hollywood, 
then was transformed into a small-screen version for Home Box Office. Now the 
one-man show will be presented with its sequel, "Life After Time," at the 
Church in Ocean Park, 235 Hill St., Santa Monica, at 8 p.m. Saturday. Tickets 
are $10. Reservations are required. For information call (213) 399-1631. JAYNE 
KAMIN ONCEA / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
